public class ReverseEachWord {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        String input = "I love Walmart";
        String[] words = input.split(" ");
        StringBuilder result = new StringBuilder();

        for (String word : words) {
            StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder(word);
            result.append(sb.reverse()).append(" ");
        }

        System.out.println(result.toString().trim());
    }
}
output- 
I evol tramlaW
-------
Split sentence into words
String[] words = input.split(" ");
Sentence ko words array me todta hai
"I love Walmart" â†’ ["I","love","Walmart"]

2ï¸âƒ£ Result store karne ke liye
StringBuilder result = new StringBuilder();

Reverse word
StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder(word);
result.append(sb.reverse()).append(" ");
StringBuilder.reverse() â†’ efficient
Space maintain karne ke liye " " add

5ï¸âƒ£ Extra space remove
result.toString().trim();

â±ï¸ Complexity
Time: O(n)
Space: O(n)

Why not use String concatenation (+)?

ğŸ‘‰ String immutable hai â†’ performance issue
ğŸ‘‰ StringBuilder efficient hai

Can you do it without split()?
Yes (manual approach):
String input = "I love Walmart";
StringBuilder word = new StringBuilder();
StringBuilder result = new StringBuilder();

for (char ch : input.toCharArray()) {
    if (ch != ' ') {
        word.append(ch);
    } else {
        result.append(word.reverse()).append(" ");
        word.setLength(0);
    }
}
result.append(word.reverse());
System.out.println(result);

What about multiple spaces?
ğŸ‘‰ Use regex:
input.split("\\s+");



